{{Portal box|Biography|History}}
'''Cristina Berm<U+00FA>dez'''<ref>''Berm<U+00FA>dez'' means "daughter of Bermudo."</ref> ([[Help:IPA for Spanish|pronunciation]]: [kristina be<U+027E>mude<U+03B8>]) was a Princess of [[Kingdom of Le<U+00F3>n|Le<U+00F3>n]] and [[Kingdom of Galicia|Galicia]]. She is also known as '''Cristina de Le<U+00F3>n'''.<ref>Cristina of Leon</ref>

== Biography ==
Cristina was a daughter of King [[Bermudo II of Le<U+00F3>n|Bermudo II the Gouty]] and his first wife, Queen [[Velasquita Ram<U+00ED>rez]].<ref>Simon Barton and [[Richard A. Fletcher]] (2000), ''The World of El Cid: Chronicles of the Spanish Reconquest'' (Manchester: Manchester University Press).</ref><ref>''Medieval Queenship'' by [[John Parsons|John C. Parsons]]. New York: St. Martin's Press, 1998. Page 260.</ref><ref>{{cite book| author = [[Alfonso de Ceballos-Escalera y Gila]]|title= ''Reyes de Le<U+00F3>n: Ordo<U+00F1>o III (951-956), Sancho I(956-966), Ordo<U+00F1>o IV (958-959), Ramiro III (966-985), Vermudo II (982-999)''|year= 2000|editorial = La Olmeda|isbn= 84-89915-11-3}}</ref>

Her grandparents were King [[Ordo<U+00F1>o III of Le<U+00F3>n]]<ref>{{cite book| apellidos = Del Arco y Garay| nombre = Ricardo|enlaceautor = Ricardo del Arco y Garay|title= Sepulcros de la Casa Real de Castilla|editorial= Instituto Jer<U+00F3>nimo Zurita. Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient<U+00ED>ficas|year= 1954|oclc = 11366237}}
* Rodr<U+00ED>guez Fern<U+00E1>ndez, Justiniano:  ''Ordo<U+00F1>o III'' Ediciones Leonesas, S.A.(1982) ISBN 84-86013-04-6</ref> and Queen [[Urraca Fern<U+00E1>ndez]].<ref>Alfonso Ceballos-Escalera, ''Reyes de Le<U+00F3>n''. ISBN 84-89915-11-3</ref>

Cristina<U+2019>s stepmother was [[Elvira of Castile, Queen of Le<U+00F3>n|Elvira Garc<U+00ED>a]] and her half-siblings were [[Alfonso V of Le<U+00F3>n|Alfonso the Noble]], Teresa and Sancha.<ref>Elorza, Juan C.; Lourdes Vaquero, Bel<U+00E9>n Castillo, Marta Negro (1990). ''El Pante<U+00F3>n Real de las Huelgas de Burgos''. ''Los enterramientos de los reyes de Le<U+00F3>n y de Castilla'' (2<U+00AA> edici<U+00F3>n). ''Editorial Evergr<U+00E1>ficas S.A., Junta de Castilla y Le<U+00F3>n. Consejer<U+00ED>a de Cultura y Bienestar Social''. ISBN 84-241-9999-5.</ref> She was an aunt of Princess [[Sancha of Le<U+00F3>n]].

In 1010, Cristina married Prince Ordo<U+00F1>o Ram<U+00ED>rez, son of [[Ramiro III of Le<U+00F3>n]]<ref>[[Reinhart Dozy]], ''Histoire des Musulmans d'espagne'' (1932).</ref> and [[Sancha G<U+00F3>mez]]. They had children:
*''Don'' Alfonso Ord<U+00F3><U+00F1>ez, who had a daughter called Cristina
*''Do<U+00F1>a'' Aldonza Ord<U+00F3><U+00F1>ez, wife of ''Don'' Pelayo Froilaz
*''Don'' Ordo<U+00F1>o Ord<U+00F3><U+00F1>ez, named after his father
*''Do<U+00F1>a'' Pelaya Ord<U+00F3><U+00F1>ez<ref>{{cite book
| author = Margarita Torre
| title= Linajes nobiliarios de Le<U+00F3>n y Castilla: Siglos IX-XIII
| year= 1985
| editorial = Salamanca: Junta de Castilla y Le<U+00F3>n
| id = ISBN 84-7846-781-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite book
| author = Calleja Puerta, Miguel
| title= El conde Suero Verm<U+00FA>dez, su parentela y su entorno social: La aristocracia asturleonesa en los siglos XI y XII
| a<U+00F1>o = 2001
| editorial = KRK Ediciones
| id = ISBN 84-95401-68-1}}</ref>

After her husband died, Cristina become a nun and lived in [[Monasterio de San Salvador (Cornellana)|Monasterio de San Salvador]].

